Allstate, Pfizer, Travelers U.S. Steel: U.S. Equity Movers

-- B y   N i k o l a j   G a m m e l t o f t   a n d   J e f f   K e a r n s
-- 
2011-08-29T20:29:43Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-28/autonation-capital-one-financial-pfizer-u-s-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in U.S. trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of 4 p.m. in New York.  Insurers rose as Hurricane Irene’s estimated cost to the
industry fell to about $2.6 billion, according to Kinetic
Analysis Corp., a firm that predicts the effects of disasters.
That’s below a projection last week of as much as $14 billion.  Allstate Corp. (ALL)   gained 8.5 percent to $26.30,  Aflac
Inc. (AFL)   advanced 4.9 percent to $37.29,  MetLife Inc. (MET)   climbed 5.9 percent to $33.31,  Lincoln National Corp. (LNC)   increased 8.9 percent to $21 and  Hartford Financial Services
Group Inc. (HIG)   gained 13 percent to $19.42. Travelers Cos.
(TRV US) climbed 5.1 percent to $50.75.  Companies that may be involved in rebuilding after
Hurricane Irene advanced.  Masco Corp. (MAS)  , the insulation
installer, rose 9.9 percent to $8.85 for the second-biggest gain
in the  Standard & Poor’s 500 . U.S. Steel Corp. (X US) the
largest U.S. steelmaker by volume, increased 9 percent to
$30.04.  AK Steel Holding Corp. (AKS)  , the third-largest U.S.
steelmaker, added 6.1 percent $9.10.  Titanium Metals Corp. (TIE)   rose 8.9 percent to $15.41.  Amazon.com Inc. (AMZN)   rose 3.6 percent to $206.53, the
highest price since Aug. 3. The internet retailer’s new tablet
sales may cut into rival Apple Inc.’s (AAPL US) and reach 5
million in the fourth-quarter, according to a Forrester analyst
report cited by Reuters. The tablet may be introduced in
October, the Wall Street Journal said.  Bank of America Corp. (BAC)   rose 8.1 percent to $8.39,
the most in the  Dow Jones Industrial Average . The largest U.S.
lender agreed to sell about half its stake in China Construction
Bank Corp. for a $3.3 billion gain, bolstering capital to help
comply with international standards that may be imposed as
regulators try to prevent a repeat of the 2008 financial crisis.  Jones Group Inc. (JNY)   jumped 8.4 percent to $11.44, the
highest price since Aug. 3. The maker of Nine West shoes may
rise to $20 if the U.S. stays out of another recession and the
company’s profitability improves, Barron’s said.  Miller Energy Resources Inc. (MILL US) rallied 61 percent,
the most in the Russell 2000 Index, to $3.65. The Huntsville,
Tennessee-based oil producer said that the regulatory filing of
a deficient version of its annual report on July 29 was a
“mistake by company personnel” and that no one had
“intentionally or knowingly” violated any securities laws.  Monsanto Co. (MON)   fell 1.3 percent to $69.78 for the
biggest decline in the  S&P 500 . Corn plants that the agriculture
products company genetically modified to thwart an insect are
falling prey to the pest in some Iowa fields, the Wall Street
Journal reported.  Pfizer Inc. (PFE)   added 3.7 percent to $18.88, the
highest price since Aug. 1. The world’s largest drugmaker won
U.S. approval to sell a drug to treat  lung cancer . The
treatment, crizotinib, is the leading candidate among more than
20 tumor-fighting medicines the company is developing to help
replace sales expected to be lost to generic drugs.  Venoco Inc. (VQ)   surged 31 percent, the most since
October 2008, to $11.76. The oil and gas exploration company got
an offer from Chief Executive Officer Timothy M. Marquez, who
owns 50.3 percent, to buy the remaining outstanding stock at
$12.50 a share.  To contact the reporters on this story:
